<p>In the interwar period European countries fully encouraged enthusiasm for sports among their citizens and even gave «technical» support. It is well-known that in Lviv on the days of important sports events an additional tramway #11A circulated through the city—from the train station to Stryiskyi Park. In many cities the public was directly involved in important matches or competitions by live broadcasts from loudspeakers on downtown streets. In Lviv public sports broadcasts could be heard on Academic Street (now Prospect Shevchenko). </p>
<p>Sports’ ability to unite people quickly in great communal solidarity was one of the most effective instruments of mass politics. Here is how a spectator describes a street audience listening to a broadcast of a football match in Warsaw 1936:</p>
<p>«There it is! Goal! The crowd buzzes and shakes. Joy shines on their faces. A cry resounds: Long may they live! The hats of young enthusiasts fly high over their heads. But not only youth are caught up in enthusiasm. Some bearded merchant in a long coat claps his hands fiercely and yells: Bravo, encore! And here’s some old woman in an old-style coat who devoutly places her hands in prayer and whispers with wrinkled lips: Oh my God, Oh my God... I bet that as long as she’s lived, she’s never seen a football match, never been to a stadium, but the powerful wave of the joy of victory has captured her.»</p>
